Every time I speak in front of an audience, whatever I say, there are mockeries on social media calling for the rejection of my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election, exposing the politics of the Centre and telling me that I should not be a member of Labour.
And that's just what I'm going through.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments to my address are generally political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who deal with a flood of sexist or racist reactions every day, but do not allow themselves to be intimidated.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era of politics is that serious abuses are apparently considered normal.
Jeremy Corbyn claimed last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that broad church, and with every ‘motivation of mistrust’ or change of selection rules, the party becomes more narrow-minded.
I have been advised many times over the past two years to keep my head down, not just to express my opinion out loud, and then I would ‘not get into trouble’.
But I didn’t go into politics for that.
Since I joined Labour as a schoolchild 32 years ago, provoked by the neglect of the Thatcher government that literally collapsed my classroom, I have always advocated better public services for those who need them most, both in my role as a city councillor and in my role as minister.
I have never hidden my politics, not even in the last election.
Everyone in Nottingham East had clarity on my policy positions and my disagreements with the current leadership.
To those who promoted the motion on Friday, I can only say one thing: when the country drags on to a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But actually I have only one message, and it is not addressed to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are Labour members or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that threats to reject my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election or political opportunities will not stop me from acting according to what I believe is in your best interests.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
