John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have an excellent track record of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with yet another set of excellent exam results, and moreover individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other initiatives across the community.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects par excellence within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students studying foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated with SCIS, shows that 72 percent of the students achieved a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of the students achieved German, 69 percent of the students French and 63 percent of the students Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as subject choice as much as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that of the obstacles to filling vacancies, 17 percent were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more and more jobs requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, in the future he will have a real advantage with such a skill for life.
Communicating directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an edge over the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. French was the only language that exceeded 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today’s children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot be denied that languages remain vital for the future of the country in a global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered ‘international communication skills.’
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
