North Korea says it will ‘under no circumstances’ unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions are leading to increasing distrust in the United States and that under such circumstances, the country could in no case unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile testing, dismantling the site for nuclear testing, and promising not to distribute nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We don’t see a similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will in no case unilaterally disarm.”
Although Ri reiterated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it takes further steps, he noted that he did not disapprove of unilateral denuclearization a priori, as Pyongyang used to do.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the very first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim promised to work towards the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way and even by objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an air castle of the people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions only increase our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, something the US leader suggested earlier in the week at the United Nations.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other party to this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a deadlock.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different from last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles would be aimed at the U.S. mainland after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to completely destroy North Korea last year, praised Kim at the United Nations this year for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said there is still much to be done and that sanctions should continue until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for this: “Whether it’s two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of the U.N. Security Council sanctions must be vigorously and firmly pursued until we have achieved complete, definitive, verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006 to greatly reduce funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
Just hours after he left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, North Korea accused him of making “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea promised this month during a meeting with Moon to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States would take “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim had told him that the “appropriate measures” he wanted were security guarantees that Trump had promised in Singapore, and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night long while drinking plenty of caffeine.
One professor noted that students at the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basics of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, drew up the course. As far as he knows, it is unique in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech about the influence of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only getting to hear this now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being organized for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was determined that students had a severe sleep deficit during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, the students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise devices and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine at bedtime.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Using a campus map, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
‘We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we feel they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know what consequences the choice of cigarettes has on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of one-night studying still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to prepare the course, having attended the professor’s class last year when he was in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar program of study before coming to the competitive setting.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, and not just an alarm to get up. They should also be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” of electronics screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, causing you to have trouble falling asleep.
