Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from the almanac of our ‘Sunday Morning': September 30, 1882, today exactly 136 years ago, for those who can TELL well... the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm ‘Hans' Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device called the Geiger counter.
Since then, the Geiger counter has been an indispensable part of science, and has also become an icon in pop culture, for example in ‘Bells or Coronado’, a 1950 film with the at first sight unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: ‘What the hell is that?’
Rogers: ‘This is a Geiger counter, which is used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can hear the effect of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.”
Evans: ‘It’s really popping now!’
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains relevant.
