HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China reports that the number of Chinese people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 14%.
Health authorities say it has affected more than 820,000 people in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, 40,000 new cases were reported.
In the vast majority of new cases, the diseases were passed on through sex, which was not the case before.
HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China through transfusions of contaminated blood.
But the number of people contracting HIV in this way is now almost zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, compared to the same period last year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 people.
The transmission of HIV through sex is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality has not been punishable in China since 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be widespread.
According to studies, 70 to 90% of men who have sex with men eventually marry a woman.
Often the diseases are transmitted by inadequate protection in sexual relations in these relationships.
The Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication since 2003 as part of efforts to address the problem.
