Ramirez claims that the Supreme Court candidate showed his genitals to her at a party during the time they were both studying at Yale in the 1980s.
The inventor of the World Wide Web plans a new Internet to tackle Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, starts a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project from the technology legend, is a company based on Berners-Lee’s open source platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that “world domination” is the guiding thought behind Inrupt.
“We have to do this now,” he said of the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to enable people to create their own ‘personal online data storage’ or POD.
It can store lists of contacts, activity lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available together through one browser and all at the same time.
What makes POD unique is the fact that it completely depends on the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this “personal empowerment through data.”
The idea behind Inrupt, according to CEO John Bruce, is that the company provides the resources, processes, and skills needed to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some developers contracted to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized apps with the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team will not be in talks with “Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a full transformation that will turn all their business models completely upside down in one go.”
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a post on Medium published Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that the “mission (of Inrupt) is to deliver the commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web that is being built on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Even after the start of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain as founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this new era for the web,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: clergyman and bearer of the Victoria Cross from World War I honored
The only Church of England clergyman to have earned a Victoria Cross during World War I as a soldier is honored 100 years later in his birthplace.
Lieutenant-Colonel, the Reverend Bernard Vann received the award following the attack at Bellenglise and Lehaucourt on 29 September 1918.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later, so he never knew he had the highest British military honour.
A memorial stone was unveiled by his two grandsons during a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of the grandsons, Michael Vann, said it was “brilliantly symbolic” that the stone was unveiled exactly 100 years after the fact for which his grandfather was distinguished.
According to the London Gazette, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion on 29 September 1918 across the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in a very dense fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns".
He later stormed on to the firing line and led the line forward before running alone to a field gun and taking out three members of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just over one month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I can never match, but also something that makes me feel humble.”
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also laid a wreath after the parade that was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he "felt very honored to play a role in the parade" and added that "the bravery of a real hero is evident from the support he receives from a large number of people".
