Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt ‘inferior’ because of his sexual orientation
Olympic jumper Tom Daley says he felt inferior during his childhood because of his sexual orientation, but that this gave him the motivation to become successful.
The twenty-four-year-old said that until he went to secondary school, he didn’t realize that “not everyone is the way I am.”
In a talk on Desert Island Discs on Radio 4 with Lauren Laverne, he said he had spoken out about gay rights to give others “hope.”
He also said that parenting had helped him put less value on winning at the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, the regular host of the long-running show, took a few months off due to illness.
Appearing as an outcast on Laverne’s first program, Daley said he felt “less” than others during his childhood because it was “socially unacceptable to like both girls and boys.”
“To this day, those feelings, the feeling of being less and the feeling of being different, are really existing facts that have given me the strength to be successful.”
He wanted to prove that he was “someone” so he wouldn’t disappoint people if they eventually found out about his orientation.
The winner of two bronze Olympic medals has become a standout campaigner for the LGBT community and used his presence at this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said that he spoke because he considered himself lucky that he could live openly without further consequences and that he wanted to give others “hope”.
The three-time world champion said that the fact that he fell in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Back, whom he met in 2013, “completely surprised me.”
Daley married the Oscar winner last year, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference had never been a problem.
"When you have to endure so much so young," he participated in his first Olympic Games at the age of fourteen and his father died three years later from cancer, it is difficult to find someone in your own age group who has experienced the same highs and lows.
The couple became parents to a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley in June and Daley said his "whole perspective" had changed.
“If you had asked me this question last year, I would have replied that it was all about winning a gold medal,” he said.
“But you know what, there are more important things on earth than winning gold Olympic medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.”
His son has the same name as his father who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father had not accepted that he would die and one of the last things he had asked was if they had already received the tickets for London 2012 because he wanted to sit in the front row.
“I couldn’t get it over my heart to say, you won’t be there to sit in the front row, Dad,” he said.
"I held his hand when he stopped breathing and not until his breathing actually stopped and he died, I could finally acknowledge that he was not invincible," he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
"I knew I'd dreamed about this all my life. Diving for a home crowd during the Olympics, there's no better feeling," he said.
It was also the inspiration for his first choice of music, Proud by Heather Small, which had greatly affected him on the way to the games and which still gave him goosebumps.
Desert Island Discs can be heard on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 BST.
