Germany's new warship delayed again
The German Navy’s newest frigate should have entered service in 2014, replacing the outdated Cold War-era warships, but it will take at least another year before it’s ready, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the 'Rheinland-Pfalz', the leading ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes a military spokesman.
The vessel should have been part of the navy in 2014, but the troubling post-delivery issues have plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels ordered by the Navy in 2007 are intended to replace the obsolete Bremen-class frigates.
As far as we know, they have a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles and a form of stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic characteristics.
Other important features are longer maintenance cycles, it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates up to two years in a row, far away from the home ports.
However, the ongoing delays mean that the advanced warships, which are intended to allow Germany to project its power overseas, are already obsolete by the time they are put into operation, Die Zeit notes.
The ill-fated frigate F125 made headlines last year, when the German navy officially refused to commission the vessel and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had sent a ship back to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons behind this return, but German media cited a number of crucial “software and hardware defects” that would render the warship useless if deployed in a combat mission.
Software failures were especially important because the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels are served by a crew of about 120 sailors, half the manpower on the frigates of the older Bremen-class.
It also became clear that the ship is suffering from a serious overweight, which will reduce performance and limit the capabilities of the Navy to carry out further upgrades.
The 'Rheinland-Pfalz' weighs 7,000 tons, which is twice as much as ships of a similar class that were used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the price tag for the entire project, including crew training, is already a problem.
This is said to have reached a staggering €3.1 billion, compared to the original €2.2 billion.
The problems that the newest frigates have in their grip become extra important because of the recent warnings that the power of the German navy is decreasing.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the parliamentary defence commission in Germany, acknowledged that the navy actually “has a shortage of deployable ships”.
The official said the problem has grown over time like a snowball, as old ships were taken out of service but no replacement vessels were delivered.
He complained that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class were yet available to be admitted to the navy.
National Trust eavesdrops on the secret lives of bats
New research conducted on an estate in the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common and small dwarf bats, the brown large-eared bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to track the bats’ activities throughout the season.
NTS employees and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's screams and what kind does what.
A map of the habitat and a report are then produced in order to create a detailed picture of their behaviour on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, conservation advisor to the NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making grasslands and how best to maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping accommodations and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
In reality, bats are not blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
At the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct investigations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s ten species of bats.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for the bats.
“Here in Threave, we have a great environment for bats,” he said.
"We have the old buildings, a lot of very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much is not yet known about bats, and that’s why the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place can lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, potentially eradicating an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to contribute to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and of many of our species, we simply don't yet know how their populations are doing."
