“When I was a kid, I used to see Scotland play at Hampden Park with my dad and it’s something that keeps attracting me.
However, that possibility would only come when I am successful in managing a club."
Ross’s predecessors as managers of Sunderland include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O’Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former boss of Alloa Athletic says he was not intimidated into becoming the successor to these established names at a major club, having previously refused advances from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Success for me is currently measured by 'can I get this club back into the Premier League?'
“Because of the structure and facilities at this club, it should undoubtedly be in the Premier League,” he said.
“It’s not an easy task to achieve this, but I can’t see myself as successful until I bring the club back there.”
Ross is only three years into his career as a manager, after a period as an assistant manager at Dumbarton and 15 months in the coaching group of Hearts.
He then helped Alloa recover from relegation to the third division and transformed St Mirren from being on the verge of relegation to winning the Championship the following season.
And Ross says he feels more comfortable now than he ever did during his career as a footballer with Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
“It was probably really a crossroads,” he recalled when he took over the leadership of Alloa.
“I really believed that management was the right choice for me, much more than playing.
It sounds bizarre, because I was doing pretty well, I earned fairly well and I have known a few reasonable highlights.
Football can be tough.
There are a lot of things that you face every week.
I still have that, given the stress and pressure of the profession, but management just feels good.
I’ve always wanted to be a manager, and now that I’m a manager, I’m as good in my own skin as I’ve ever felt in my adult life.”
