The most significant escalation became known this week when new effective, increased tax rates were revealed for $200 billion (€150 billion) in goods; half of all goods coming from China to the US.
Beijing has taken in-kind reprisals every time, most recently by raising tariffs from 5 to 10% for $60 billion worth of U.S. goods.
China has pledged to match the U.S. every time, and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to blink.
For Washington to bow, requests must be granted, but public bowing to the US is far too painful for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
However, experts argue that if Beijing plays smart, the trade war with the US could support China positively in the longer term, as the interdependence between the two economies decreases.
“The fact that a rapid political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that could put either country in an economic free fall is actually much more dangerous than viewers have previously acknowledged,” said Abigail Grace, a research associate at the Center for a New American Security, a think tank specializing in national security issues that focuses on Asia.
