Red glow update: Concentrations are decreasing in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission shows a general decline in concentrations of red glow in parts of Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the US).
According to the committee, there is a report of a fragmentary increase of the red glow in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which could indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Glow stretches over an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
There are spots about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Red glow has also been seen in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported off the coast of Pinellas County over the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations near or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations near or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are ongoing reports of respiratory irritation in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
In northwestern Florida, there was no mention of respiratory irritation in the past week.
